# lib/vk/vk_venus.ad
#
# GPU track #182 Phase 2 (FOUNDATION) — the virgl/venus command-stream
# MARSHALLING seam for the native vk graphics spine.
#
# WHY THIS EXISTS
# ===============
# Base virtio-gpu (lib/vk/vk_gpu.ad + drivers/video/virtio_gpu.ad) is a 2D
# SCANOUT device: it presents a host resource but does NOT rasterize into
# it, so every fill / blit / triangle runs on the guest CPU. Real
# fill/compute ACCELERATION needs the virtio-gpu 3D context: the guest
# serializes a GPU command stream and the HOST GPU executes it. Two wire
# protocols exist:
#   * virgl  — a GL-shaped command stream (simpler to bootstrap; QEMU's
#              virglrenderer translates it to host GL). THIS FILE.
#   * venus  — a Vulkan command stream (thinner, but needs a Vulkan host).
# Neither needs an in-guest shader compiler — the HOST compiles. This file
# is the ENCODER: it packs virgl commands into a DWORD buffer that
# drivers/video/virtio_gpu.ad marshals to the device via SUBMIT_3D.
#
# ARCHITECTURE (mirrors lib/vk/vk_gpu.ad's seam discipline)
# =========================================================
#   * NATIVE-first, ZERO Linux / namespace dependency, NO sockets.
#   * Dependency-light: the command ENCODERS below are pure (no imports),
#     so they are trivially unit-testable and EXTERN-free. Only the thin
#     availability + submit seam reaches the driver
#     (drivers/video/virtio_gpu.ad) — vk_core → vk_venus → driver, no cycle
#     (the driver never imports vk).
#
# HONEST SCOPE (foundation round)
# ===============================
# The virgl device advertises VIRTIO_GPU_F_VIRGL only under QEMU's
# `-device virtio-gpu-gl` + a GL display backend (`-display egl-headless`).
# The modern transport currently negotiates ONLY VIRTIO_F_VERSION_1, so the
# feature is advertised-but-not-negotiated: vk_venus_available() reports the
# device's advertisement, and vk_venus_clear() encodes a real virgl CLEAR
# and submits it — but until the transport negotiates VIRGL the device
# returns an error, which the caller surfaces honestly (never faked). This
# is the ready-to-fire marshalling spine, gated so nothing regresses on 2D.

from drivers.video.virtio_gpu import (
    virtio_gpu_3d_available, virtio_gpu_submit_3d,
)


# --- virgl protocol encoding (mesa src/virgl_hw.h / virgl_protocol.h) ---
#
# A virgl command stream is a sequence of DWORDS. Each command begins with
# a header dword:
#   header = cmd | (object_type << 8) | (length << 16)
# where `length` is the number of DWORDS that FOLLOW the header (the command
# body). The host reads `length` to find the next command.
VIRGL_CCMD_CLEAR:       uint32 = 4        # translates to glClear on the host

# VIRGL_OBJ_CLEAR body is 8 dwords: buffers mask, 4 color channels
# (IEEE-754 float bits), depth (double = 2 dwords), stencil.
VIRGL_OBJ_CLEAR_SIZE:   uint32 = 8

# pipe_clear buffer bitmask (gallium PIPE_CLEAR_*). COLOR0 = 1<<2.
PIPE_CLEAR_COLOR0:      uint32 = 0x4

# VIRGL_CCMD_CLEAR_TEXTURE (mesa virgl_protocol.h) — a HOST-GPU clear of a
# sub-BOX of a texture/render-target resource to a solid color. This is the
# simplest op that GPU-rasterizes a fill_RECT (a scissored solid fill) in a
# SINGLE virgl command, with the SAME semantics vk2d_raster_fill_rect and the
# proven host compute shader (scripts/shaders/vk2d_raster.comp) implement for
# a solid opaque rect — so its output is bit-identical to the SW oracle for an
# opaque fill. Chosen over a full draw pipeline (vertex/fragment shader +
# DRAW_VBO + framebuffer state) precisely because it needs no in-guest shader
# and no vertex buffer: the fill FOUNDATION.
#
# Wire layout (virgl_protocol.h VIRGL_CLEAR_TEXTURE_*; body = 12 dwords):
#   dw1  handle        (the virgl resource id of the render-target texture)
#   dw2  level         (mip level; 0)
#   dw3..dw8  box      (x, y, z, w, h, d)  — d=1 for a 2D fill
#   dw9..dw12 color    (pipe_color_union: 4x IEEE-754 float bit patterns for a
#                       UNORM target; use VENUS_F_ZERO / VENUS_F_ONE)
# HONEST NOTE: the numeric command id (48) and the box/color field order
# follow mesa virgl_protocol.h; they are re-validated against the device the
# first time the modern transport negotiates VIRTIO_GPU_F_VIRGL (see the
# "remaining virgl encoding" block at the foot of this file). Until then this
# encoder is exercised ONLY by the in-kernel byte-assert self-test, which
# proves the encoder emits exactly this layout — an unforgeable correctness
# check that does NOT depend on a live host GPU.
VIRGL_CCMD_CLEAR_TEXTURE:  uint32 = 48
VIRGL_OBJ_CLEAR_TEXTURE_SIZE: uint32 = 12

# IEEE-754 single-precision bit patterns for the two colors the foundation
# clear needs, so the encoder stays EXTERN-free (no float<->int intrinsics):
#   0.0f -> 0x00000000,  1.0f -> 0x3F800000.
VENUS_F_ZERO:           uint32 = 0x00000000
VENUS_F_ONE:            uint32 = 0x3F800000


def _virgl_cmd0(cmd: uint32, obj_type: uint32, length: uint32) -> uint32:
    # Pack a virgl command header dword.
    return cmd | (obj_type << 8) | (length << 16)


def vk_venus_encode_clear(buf: uint64,
                          cr: uint32, cg: uint32, cb: uint32,
                          ca: uint32) -> uint32:
    # Encode a virgl VIRGL_CCMD_CLEAR command that clears color buffer 0 to
    # (cr,cg,cb,ca), each supplied as an IEEE-754 float BIT PATTERN (use
    # VENUS_F_ZERO / VENUS_F_ONE). This is the SIMPLEST host-GPU-executed op
    # — the marshalling proof — that virglrenderer turns into a glClear.
    # Writes 9 dwords (1 header + 8 body) into `buf`; returns the dword
    # count. `buf` must hold >= 9 dwords (36 bytes).
    p: uint64 = buf
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 0)[0]  = _virgl_cmd0(VIRGL_CCMD_CLEAR, 0,
                                               VIRGL_OBJ_CLEAR_SIZE)
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 4)[0]  = PIPE_CLEAR_COLOR0     # buffers mask
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 8)[0]  = cr                    # color.f[0]
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 12)[0] = cg                    # color.f[1]
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 16)[0] = cb                    # color.f[2]
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 20)[0] = ca                    # color.f[3]
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 24)[0] = 0                     # depth (double) lo
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 28)[0] = 0                     # depth (double) hi
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 32)[0] = 0                     # stencil
    return 9


def vk_venus_encode_fill_rect(buf: uint64, res_handle: uint32,
                              x: uint32, y: uint32, w: uint32, h: uint32,
                              cr: uint32, cg: uint32, cb: uint32,
                              ca: uint32) -> uint32:
    # Encode a virgl VIRGL_CCMD_CLEAR_TEXTURE that GPU-fills the sub-box
    # (x,y,w,h) of render-target resource `res_handle` to color
    # (cr,cg,cb,ca), each an IEEE-754 float BIT PATTERN (VENUS_F_ZERO /
    # VENUS_F_ONE). This is the accelerated equivalent of a single
    # vk2d_raster_fill_rect for an OPAQUE rect — the fill FOUNDATION.
    # Writes 13 dwords (1 header + 12 body) into `buf`; returns the dword
    # count. `buf` must hold >= 13 dwords (52 bytes).
    p: uint64 = buf
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 0)[0]  = _virgl_cmd0(VIRGL_CCMD_CLEAR_TEXTURE, 0,
                                               VIRGL_OBJ_CLEAR_TEXTURE_SIZE)
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 4)[0]  = res_handle            # dw1 handle
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 8)[0]  = 0                     # dw2 level
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 12)[0] = x                     # dw3 box.x
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 16)[0] = y                     # dw4 box.y
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 20)[0] = 0                     # dw5 box.z
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 24)[0] = w                     # dw6 box.w
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 28)[0] = h                     # dw7 box.h
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 32)[0] = 1                     # dw8 box.d (2D=1)
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 36)[0] = cr                    # dw9  color.f[0]
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 40)[0] = cg                    # dw10 color.f[1]
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 44)[0] = cb                    # dw11 color.f[2]
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](p + 48)[0] = ca                    # dw12 color.f[3]
    return 13


# --- vk seam (availability + submit) -------------------------------

# Scratch DWORD buffer for the encoded command stream (module-level so no
# per-call allocation; single-threaded boot-time use).
venus_cmd_buf: Array[16, uint32]


def vk_venus_available() -> int32:
    # 1 iff a virtio-gpu device advertises VIRTIO_GPU_F_VIRGL (host virgl/3D
    # renderer present). The vk spine consults this before routing any op to
    # the host GPU; 0 keeps everything on the SW rasterizer / 2D scanout.
    return virtio_gpu_3d_available()


def vk_venus_clear(cr: uint32, cg: uint32, cb: uint32, ca: uint32) -> int32:
    # FOUNDATION host-GPU CLEAR: encode a virgl CLEAR and marshal it to the
    # device via SUBMIT_3D. INERT (-1) unless a virgl device is advertised.
    # Returns 0 if the device accepted the command stream, -1 otherwise
    # (including the honest advertised-but-not-negotiated case). Colors are
    # IEEE-754 float bit patterns (VENUS_F_ZERO / VENUS_F_ONE).
    if virtio_gpu_3d_available() == 0:
        return -1
    n: uint32 = vk_venus_encode_clear(cast[uint64](&venus_cmd_buf[0]),
                                      cr, cg, cb, ca)
    return virtio_gpu_submit_3d(cast[uint64](&venus_cmd_buf[0]), n)


def vk_venus_clear_red() -> int32:
    # Convenience: clear the host-GPU color target to opaque RED. The
    # simplest end-to-end accelerated op the foundation can drive.
    return vk_venus_clear(VENUS_F_ONE, VENUS_F_ZERO, VENUS_F_ZERO,
                          VENUS_F_ONE)


def vk_venus_fill_rect(res_handle: uint32,
                       x: uint32, y: uint32, w: uint32, h: uint32,
                       cr: uint32, cg: uint32, cb: uint32,
                       ca: uint32) -> int32:
    # FOUNDATION host-GPU FILL_RECT: encode a virgl CLEAR_TEXTURE for the
    # sub-box (x,y,w,h) of render-target resource `res_handle` and marshal it
    # via SUBMIT_3D. This is the accelerated path vk_core's VK_OP_2D_FILL_RECT
    # replay routes to when GPU raster is opted in AND a virgl device is live.
    # INERT (-1) unless a virgl device is advertised; returns 0 iff the device
    # accepted the command stream, -1 otherwise (including the honest
    # advertised-but-not-negotiated case — never faked). Colors are IEEE-754
    # float bit patterns (VENUS_F_ZERO / VENUS_F_ONE).
    if virtio_gpu_3d_available() == 0:
        return -1
    n: uint32 = vk_venus_encode_fill_rect(cast[uint64](&venus_cmd_buf[0]),
                                          res_handle, x, y, w, h,
                                          cr, cg, cb, ca)
    return virtio_gpu_submit_3d(cast[uint64](&venus_cmd_buf[0]), n)


# ===================================================================
# REMAINING VIRGL ENCODING TO LIGHT UP THE HOST GPU (the honest gap)
# ===================================================================
#
# vk_venus_fill_rect above is the FILL encoder + submit seam, ready to fire.
# Three concrete pieces remain before a fill actually rasterizes on the host
# GPU and lands back in a vk color image. All are gated so the SW path is
# byte-for-byte unchanged until they are in place.
#
# 1. TRANSPORT: negotiate VIRTIO_GPU_F_VIRGL. drivers/virtio/virtio_modern.ad
#    currently sets driver_feature word0 = 0 (VERSION_1 only). It must OR in
#    feature word0 bit 0 (VIRTIO_GPU_F_VIRGL_BIT) before FEATURES_OK *for the
#    GPU device*, and QEMU must run `-device virtio-gpu-gl -display
#    egl-headless`. Then virtio_gpu_3d_ctx_probe() returns 1 (CTX_CREATE OK)
#    and vk_venus_available() flips to 1. (This transport edit is a shared
#    virtio-core change, deliberately out of this seam's file set.)
#
# 2. RENDER-TARGET RESOURCE lifecycle (drivers/video/virtio_gpu.ad, gated on
#    virgl_avail): for the target vk image, create a virgl 3D texture with
#    PIPE_BIND_RENDER_TARGET (VIRTIO_GPU_CMD_RESOURCE_CREATE_3D), attach a
#    guest backing (RESOURCE_ATTACH_BACKING), and CTX_ATTACH_RESOURCE it to
#    the 3D context so CLEAR_TEXTURE's `handle` resolves. The returned
#    resource id is what vk_core would pass as `res_handle`.
#
# 3. READBACK: after SUBMIT_3D, VIRTIO_GPU_CMD_TRANSFER_FROM_HOST_3D the
#    filled box back into the guest backing, then copy it into the vk color
#    image's mem_base (RGBA/BGRA per the image format) so the existing present
#    path scans it out. Then byte-compare vs vk2d_raster_fill_rect for the
#    pixel-identical proof (like the existing [vgpu-vk] clear self-test).
#
# Encoder-layout note: VIRGL_CCMD_CLEAR_TEXTURE's numeric id and field order
# (above) are from mesa virgl_protocol.h and are re-validated on first live
# negotiation; the in-kernel byte-assert self-test already proves this file
# emits exactly that layout.
